commit_message:
update_router(): Consolidate all commands in one transaction

This patch is modifying the update_router() method - and all the related
methods - to consolidade all commands into a single transaction.

This ensures consistency when updating the router resource since now all
changes to OVSDB are chained.

Change-Id: Ic06bdfcdc0f871e925e5a957ff29c290072bd02c

commit_message:
Set dhcp_agent_notification to False for devstack

This avoids DHCP agent scheduling for non-router ports and eliminates
their WARNING logs[1].
But, this option does not work for router ports because they are out of
control[2] and seems there is no other similar option for router ports.

[1]neutron-server[5675]: WARNING neutron.scheduler.dhcp_agent_scheduler ... No more DHCP agents
   neutron-server[5675]: WARNING neutron.api.rpc.agentnotifiers.dhcp_rpc_agent_api ...
   Unable to schedule network cad77229-963b-492a-8213-f67cabde3b4d: no agents available; will retry on subsequent port and subnet creation events.
[2]https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/a1aff7a4dce5b66e7228fe1c4cf3975194f9ec8c/neutron/api/rpc/agentnotifiers/dhcp_rpc_agent_api.py#L58-L71

Change-Id: I118f5d5c92e527c8c0ec5118d45eb58aac9d0c84
Signed-off-by: Dong Jun <dongj@dtdream.com>

commit_message:
Remove triplicated update_router_routes() method

There were 3 instances of the same method spreaded around the OVN code.
This patch removes the duplicated ones leaving only one definition as
part of the OVNClient class.

commit_message:
Added zuulv3 jobs for testing neutron tempest plugin

* In order to test the tempest plugin, this patch adds following
  jobs against neutron repo.
  - neutron-tempest-plugin-api for api tests
  - neutron-tempest-plugin-dvr-multinode-scenario and
    neutron-tempest-plugin-scenario-linuxbridge for scenario tests

Depends-On: I42d389836e72813fdeebc797a577f4a8ac2ee603
Change-Id: Iab7f7bcec9597444041c6d6891b5e0d9a03ba039

[{'created': '2017-11-13 14:38:51.000000000', 'message': 'Update murano-cfapi-paste.ini with http_proxy_to_wsgi

Commit 02ec8d03ed53660470ae7623b7c0528a6207e97d updated
murano-paste.ini with http_proxy_to_wsgi. This commit does
the same to murano-cxfapi-paste.ini.

Murano used to have a custom, always-enabled ssl middleware, to parse
X-Forwarded-Proto header, to let murano work correctly behind an SSL
proxy. There is now an oslo middleware, that does the
same thing, but more thoroughly.

This commit replaces custom implementation with oslo one.

Change-Id: I7b12305de2b148cdcc629eaeb131869f50180832
Closes-Bug: #1731927
'}]
commit_message:
Update murano-cfapi-paste.ini with http_proxy_to_wsgi

Commit 02ec8d03ed53660470ae7623b7c0528a6207e97d updated
murano-paste.ini with http_proxy_to_wsgi. This commit does
the same to murano-cxfapi-paste.ini.

Murano used to have a custom, always-enabled ssl middleware, to parse
X-Forwarded-Proto header, to let murano work correctly behind an SSL
proxy. There is now an oslo middleware, that does the
same thing, but more thoroughly.

This commit replaces custom implementation with oslo one.

Change-Id: I7b12305de2b148cdcc629eaeb131869f50180832
Closes-Bug: #1731927

commit_message:
Fix kolla tests

Jinja2==2.10 adds a namespace function here

https://github.com/pallets/jinja/blob/master/jinja2/utils.py#L615

That gets renamed in the tests as the default namespace making the tests
fail.

I've renamed the variable namespace to basenamespace to avoid the issue

Change-Id: I9bf50032c0a284acd4cc30d3b3854eb00f018d86
Partial-Bug: #1732140

commit_message:
Fix test_get_volume_config method

The current test does not check instance variables of
LibvirtConfigGuestDisk object.
So fix the test to check attributes of LibvirtConfigGuestDisk
object.

Change-Id: I14fb44eebf9d6f7623225dea46d143f7cb84d7fc
Closes-Bug: #1706399

block_device_mapping_v2.bus_type is missing from api-ref

block_device_mapping_v2.bus_type is missing from
POST /servers API reference. This patch add it.

Closes-Bug: #1713895

commit_message:
Fix the expirer cron task to run correctly

We need to escape % for cron to run correctly. Without
this the cron task fails with syntax error.

Change-Id: I8eac2d978380ccc1c6998929c8aa6a440ed4bcce

[{'created': '2017-10-12 15:30:31.000000000', 'message': 'Implement "dns-backend" binding

This patchset implements "dns-backend" binding which is required to
properly handle DNS zone transfers between designate and
desigante-bind applications. If "dns-backend" binding is provided
when deploying designate and designate-bind applications, DNZ zone
transfers will now take place over the subnet which belongs to the
provided space.

Depends-On: https://github.com/openstack/charm-interface-bind-rndc/pull/1
Depends-On: Icbe0cc790c565f125f0fe8c903e9b755fe764d7c

commit_message:
Implement "dns-backend" binding

This patchset implements support for "dns-backend" binding. Use the
"dns-backend" relation network space binding to populate the list
of dns master servers in the designate pool configuration,
ensuring that communication between master and slave servers
happens over the correct network space.

Depends-On: I927e3958cf929ace9d43f8b3d9509b90b9eab60f
Depends-On: Icbe0cc790c565f125f0fe8c903e9b755fe764d7c
Change-Id: I2c7b95e630611ac16c19e7f9efb81f54802849e9
Closes-Bug: #1722794

commit_message:
Refactor Loader component

Loader component carries too much logic and this makes adding
other types of loaders complicated. (e.g. overlay loader)

This change creates BaseLoader component which handles loading
logic and Loader component is refactored into several *Loader
components which use BaseLoader internally

Modifications in other files than ui/Loader.js are just loader
component renaming

Change-Id: I8324f1467c90935d0d233d3472fd4257ae57c07d

commit_message:
Add a .htaccess for redirecting old paths

This commit adds an .htaccess file to the tempest docs to handle
redirecting old paths to the new location. Before the docs migration in
the past we had docs located at docs.openstack.org/developer/tempest and
now things are located in docs.openstack.org/tempest/latest. With this
file we should be properly redirecting old links to the new location.

Change-Id: Idec7b2f299ade9b7dcc678ea1daf8daa25f08c44

use metering api def from neutron-lib

The metering extension's API definition was rehomed into neutron-lib
with commit I1b3285287be2429f7cf9913a7e6204db26371ced. This patch
consumes the API definition removing the rehomed code from neutron
and updating references to use lib's code.

NeutronLibImpact

commit_message:
use ip allocation api def from neutron-lib

The IP allocation extension's API definition was rehomed into
neutron-lib with commit Ifebe1d5e623a16ae46598c19b7d904fe913ce2d3
This patch consumes the API definition by removing the rehomed code and
using the APIExtensionDescriptor for the extension class.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: Ic44c55f6aa2c6ea8f67f9d17e904ad695ff655df

commit_message:
Remove hdfs job from check queue

In the manila weekly community meeting it was resolved [1]
to remove unmaintained drivers from the check queue to avoid
waste of infrastructure resources and to remove "red noise"
from the gerrit review pages.

Do so for the hdfs driver.  Leave the job defined as it is run
in devstack-hdfs-plugin.

[1] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-meeting-alt/%23openstack-meeting-alt.2017-11-02.log.html#t2017-11-02T15:26:17

Change-Id: Ifdd55572e9a2ba243fe074476d9459acaf474f54

commit_message:
Add DNS APIs

OVN Northbound DB has DNS table. Support CRUD operations for
this table. These APIs will be used by networking-ovn to use
OVN's native DNS feature.

Note: ovn-nbctl do not support these APIs as of now. But it is
good to have these in ovsdbapp and it will be useful.

Partial-bug: #1688172

Change-Id: I5528829eef0a7534d9266bb3abc2aec269e4ba35

Remove cliff-tablib

This is merged with cliff and shouldn't be used separately anymore

commit_message:
[CLI] Improve Rally DB UX

- By default hide creds when running rally db show
- Add option --creds to show them
- Print results of operations as well as connection string to DB

Change-Id: Ifc8ee8ee7b38821409d29ccfe66903e891e12ad3

commit_message:
Enable in-cluster loadbalancing of kubernetes API

I originally disabled this because i couldn't successfully deploy the
API this way, but it was probably caused by garbled up node hostnames,
which was fixed in I1c0251be58535d59fe0ec157cb9acaba209e8732.

Change-Id: I0f51e971fad11568c2f9db13c0d1c54122c51f5d

commit_message:
Disable events persister per default

This change fixes devstack installation which attempts to import
Elasticsearch persister repository.

More intuitive options to control loading of repositories are
introduced:

* kafka_metrics.enabled - default=True
* kafka_alarm_history.enabled - default=True
* kafka_events.enabled - default=False

Change-Id: I78707386f2080f37746f9598ba28f738832d9c86
Story: 2001285
Task: 5833

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-07-13 01:18:01.000000000', 'message': 'sphinxext: directive for cliff app

A new directive cliff-app is introduced in this patch.
There is a case where we would like to generate a reference of
global options of a cliff application. The new directive automates
this process.

The existing autoprogram-cliff direcitive is renamed to cliff-command.
We now have two directives in the cliff sphinxext, so the previous name
is ambiguous now. It is better to use names which associates which
class (App or Command) is processed.
Note that the old name is kept for backward compatibility.

Note that a local copied version of this directive is already used
in python-neutronclient CLI reference.
https://docs.openstack.org/python-neutronclient/latest/cli/neutron-reference.html#neutron-usage

Change-Id: I20e46521a137ca721fae28f10c5cf75d26069e45
'}, {'created': '2017-10-26 06:57:59.000000000', 'message': 'sphinxext: Support cliff application

optoions of a cliff application to autoprogram-cliff directive.
If a class path of a cliff application is specified as the argument of
autoprogram-cliff directive, it will be interpreted as a cliff application
and global options of the specified application are rendered.

Change-Id: I20e46521a137ca721fae28f10c5cf75d26069e45

commit_message:
sphinxext: Support cliff application

This commit adds a feature to generate a reference of global
optoions of a cliff application to autoprogram-cliff directive.
If a class path of a cliff application is specified as the argument of
autoprogram-cliff directive, it will be interpreted as a cliff application
and global options of the specified application are rendered.

Change-Id: I20e46521a137ca721fae28f10c5cf75d26069e45

'}, {'created': '2017-11-12 13:23:32.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Resolve exceptions found in the tempest log

Fixed issues in the code revealed by exceptions in the tempest build
logs.
These were in different areas of the code:
* dnat - two issues found - reference to removed ports existed &
        uninstall and unbind methods were both calling each other.
        added a cache to identify ports in process so we will avoid
        these loop calls
* dhcp - Ports with IPv6 address only were added to the dhcp, which
        only handles IPv4 packets
* l3_proactive handler - added handling to cases where ports had no
        (or multiple) IP addresses.
* topology: minor old typo bug.

Note - DHCP should be revisited as the code assumes each port may have
just one address - which is not correct.

Change-Id: I14039b3e5752b8ecbc7505a5cb2da3965484c1f6
Closes-Bug: #1728518

commit_message:
Resolve dhcp exceptions found in the tempest log

Fixed issues in the code revealed by exceptions in the tempest build
logs.
Ports with IPv6 address only were added to the dhcp, which only handles
      IPv4 packets

Note - DHCP should be revisited as the code assumes each port may have
just one address - which is not correct.

Change-Id: I14039b3e5752b8ecbc7505a5cb2da3965484c1f6
Closes-Bug: #1728518

commit_message:
Increase the zuul tasks timeout

As some of our build tasks fail on timeout from time to time, I am
changing the timeout for the build tasks to 3 hours (10800 seconds).
Hopefully this will resolve the timeout. If not, we should check with
the openstack-infra team to find the root cause for these timeouts.

P.S. Tried the syntax in the following URL:
https://specs.openstack.org/openstack-infra/infra-specs/specs/zuulv3.html#jobs
but it still does not work - changed to seconds

Change-Id: I371430e4b4c312c034fc88f4a959bb563e53d2de

commit_message:
placement: rewrite AllocationCandidates.get_by_filters

Using the AggregatedProviderSummaryList object to implement it.

The whole process underlayer as below:
* Get a list of resource provider ids, those resource provider satisfy
  the request sources if it has. If the resource provider proviers all
  the request resources and satisfy the amount, it will be in the list.
  If resource provider providers part of request resources and satisfy
  the amount will be in the list also, will figure out whether this
  resource provider can share resource from other resource provider.
* Populate the usages based on that list of resource provider ids
* Populate the traits based on that list of resource provider ids
* Construct the a list of ProviderSummay objects based on those provider
* Building the mapping between shared and non-shared resource providers
  as AggregatedProviderSummary object.
* Filter out the AggregatedProviderSummay object doesn't have all the
  requested resources based on the resource class id.
* Generate the AllocationRequest and ProviderSummay object from the
  AggregatedProviderSummay object.

Change-Id: I65f24a9697254354f2aac18c9ee77c93f6c9e9d0
Partial-implement-blueprint add-trait-support-in-allocation-candidates

commit_message:
Add AggregatedProviderSummary and AggregatedProviderSummaryList objects

"AggregatedProviderSummaryList.get_all_with_any_resource" method will
generate a list of AggregatedProviderSummary objects based on a plain
list of ProviderSummary objects. The main goal of AggregatedProviderSummary
List object is generating the mapping of shared and non-shared resource provider.
Grouping the shared and non-shared resource provider together as an
AggregatedProviderSummary object.

So each of AggregatedProviderSummary object can be a single resource provider
which provides all the requested resources. It also can be a list of
resource providers which provides all the requested resources, those
resource providers are in the same aggregate.

The AggregatedProviderSummary hides the detail of shared or non-shared
provider. Using the AggregatedProviderSummary.has_resources method to
detect whether the provider or providers in the AggregatedProviderSummay
object can satisfy.

Change-Id: I64d3b96ccae119c4f03afa7fcbf43382a9775929
Partial-implement-blueprint add-trait-support-in-allocation-candidates

commit_message:
Add ProviderSummaryList object

The `ProviderSummaryList.get_all_with_any_resource` method
will return a plain list of resource providers, since there may
have shared or non-shared resource provider in the list. And
there is no any mapping between those shared and non-shared
resource providers. The mapping of shared and non-shared
will be processed in high layer object.

And those resource providers will satisfy the requested resources
if it has such resource. The resource provider may only has part of
requested resources and satisfy the request amount, since it has
chance to get other requested resource from shared resource provider
in the same aggregate.

The usages and traits info will be populated also.

Change-Id: Icdb4b09509cb7014399ae20d87b0a97bf2056b78
Partial-implement-blueprint add-trait-support-in-allocation-candidates

commit_message:
Enable _get_usages_by_provider_and_rc not filter on the resource class id

The resource provider summary in the allocation candidates API should include
all the resources, not only the requested resource. This patch enables the
'rc_ids' parameter can accept None value, it means not filter on the resource
class id to get usages for all the resources. In later patch, the implement
of 'AllocationCandidates.get_all_by_filters' will be rewritten, then the 'rc_ids'
parameter will be removed.

TODO(those todos may can be done after the rewrite AllocationCandidate.get_by_filters,
then the existed code doesn't depend on the current interface anymore.):
* use namedtuple instead of this
* remove uuid column, since after the rewrite, it is usell
* remove the rc_ids parameter after rewrite

Partial-implement-blueprint add-trait-support-in-allocation-candidates
Change-Id: I93bf63ab7f0ccba7b0a8b264443d80f0d7bf90c1

commit_message:
Add _get_providers_with_most_resource method

This method returns a dict, keyed by resource provider id, valued by
resource provider uuid.

Each resource provider will satisfy the requested resources if it has
such resource inventory. So this method just generate a list of
candidate resource providers, each resource provider may has part of
requested resources. We will figure out whether those resource providers
satisfy the request by sharing the resources from other resource providers
in the higher layer code.

Partial-implement-blueprint add-trait-support-in-allocation-candidates
Change-Id: I37dcfbee8524c067720f626fecbc30484f4774ba

commit_message:
Add Puppet build jobs to check and gate pipelines

In order to ensure a successful build, all puppet modules will
attempt to be built as part of puppet-release-jobs template
to ensure that it is successfully released.

Change-Id: I5fde7e7f5747f50d4703161be0ab2f797840b630

The puppet module build job mainly depends on any metadata.json
changes which generally affect version bumps.  There is no need
to run the job if we will not be building the module.

Change-Id: Iff411b4eb2bcc2c403608461d5ef313c01df9009
'}]
commit_message:
Avoid running Puppet module build job for no reason

The puppet module build job mainly depends on any metadata.json
changes which generally affect version bumps.  There is no need
to run the job if we will not be building the module.

Change-Id: Iff411b4eb2bcc2c403608461d5ef313c01df9009

commit_message:
Remove httpd logs directory mounting from swift

Swift doesn't run over httpd. So there's no need to mount the httpd log
directory.

Change-Id: Ife5a4c7ab0ffe49fd56ce911e4f7b808bfe875c9

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-09-14 04:23:06.000000000', 'message': 'Make eventlet hub use a monotonic clock

If system time is adjusted first forward and then backward while a
masakari-engine service is running, then the periodic tasks stops
for the duration of time the system clock was adjusted backward.

This was supposed to be fixed by the following patch to oslo.service
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/286838/ , but the order of imports
in unit tests and production code is different, so nova services
end up starting with the default eventlet hub, that does not use a
monotonic clock and, thus, is affected by changes of system time.

Testing the change done in the patch is problematic, as it's a
subject of imports order and is not reproduced in functional or
unit tests (oslo_service is always imported earlier than eventlet
hub is initialized, so it just does "the right thing").
The alternative is to make an assertion when services start.

This patch is the copy of below nova commit:
a7505ee648b22f5827117bcc1192b5654c29cf9c

Change-Id: I9d917b3151d9cdf7340a173b5baf98def63c76cd
Closes-Bug: #1510234
'}, {'created': '2017-09-15 04:17:25.000000000', 'message': 'Make eventlet hub use a monotonic clock

If system time is adjusted first forward and then backward while a

for the duration of time the system clock was adjusted backward.

This was supposed to be fixed by the following patch to oslo.service
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/286838/ , but the order of imports
in unit tests and production code is different, so masakari services
end up starting with the default eventlet hub, that does not use a
monotonic clock and, thus, is affected by changes of system time.

Testing the change done in the patch is problematic, as it's a
subject of imports order and is not reproduced in functional or
unit tests (oslo_service is always imported earlier than eventlet
hub is initialized, so it just does "the right thing").
The alternative is to make an assertion when services start.

Co-Authored-By: Roman Podoliaka <rpodolyaka@mirantis.com>
Closes-Bug: #1510234
Change-Id: I9d917b3151d9cdf7340a173b5baf98def63c76cd

commit_message:
Make eventlet hub use a monotonic clock

If system time is adjusted first forward and then backward while a
masakari-engine service is running, then the periodic tasks stops
for the duration of time the system clock was adjusted backward.

This was supposed to be fixed by the following patch to oslo.service
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/286838/ , but the order of imports
in unit tests and production code is different, so masakari services
end up starting with the default eventlet hub, that does not use a
monotonic clock and, thus, is affected by changes of system time.

Testing the change done in the patch is problematic, as it's a
subject of imports order and is not reproduced in functional or
unit tests (oslo_service is always imported earlier than eventlet
hub is initialized, so it just does "the right thing").
The alternative is to make an assertion when services start.

Co-Authored-By: Roman Podoliaka <rpodolyaka@mirantis.com>
Closes-Bug: #1510234
Change-Id: I9d917b3151d9cdf7340a173b5baf98def63c76cd

commit_message:
Consume horizon in-tree django variant jobs

The legacy jobs legacy-horizon-tox-py27dj1* needs to be clean up,
so it is not a good idea to consume them in horizon plugin jobs.
It prevents from pushing them away.
This commit tries to py27dj1* zuulv3 jobs defined in the horizon repo.

Needed-By: I23a95b36e73bb444f94683c801eda11fb1430aa8
Change-Id: I040b35a4830423dce6fa4279882a01b8e88ad5f9

commit_message:
[WIP][POC] Host plugin information from os-vif

This patch adds the host plugin information in the port binding
profile dict and transfered to Neutron during the port update.
In this phase, Nova updates the port with the host id (port binding).

This object (os_vif.objects.host_info.HostInfo) provides Neutron the
available VIF information of the system.

Needed patches:
- os-vif: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/441590/

Change-Id: I892918a8bad5b9dc343c379db68f3eab81cb9d5e

[{'created': '2017-09-12 13:52:52.000000000', 'message': 'Intel Fortville Dynamic Device Personalization (DDP)

Within Intel Fortville version 6, a new feature was introduced: Fortville
Dynamic Device Personalization (DDP) [1]_ to program analyzer/parser via
AdminQ A profile can be used to update FVL configuration tables via MMIO
configuration space, not microcode or firmware itself.

This spec proposes to add a new method to read from the livbirt driver the
DDP loaded profile in a network device. This new parameter will be added
to `LibvirtConfigNodeDevicePciCap` to extend the PCI NIC information.

The present feature plans to use the existing API, amending the reported
profile string to the NIC capabilities string list. Users will request
capabilities and a specific profile using the same string list in the
Neutron binding profile.

blueprint intel-fortville-ddp

Change-Id: I182ee5d5293204d0fd57188d7918bd6e14975d5d

commit_message:
Intel Fortville Dynamic Device Personalization (DDP)

Within Intel Fortville version 6, a new feature was introduced: Fortville
Dynamic Device Personalization (DDP) [1]_ to program an analyzer or parser
via AdminQ. A profile can be used to update FVL configuration tables via
MMIO configuration space; this profile is not microcode or firmware itself.

This spec proposes to add a new method to read from the libvirt driver the
DDP loaded profile in a network device. This new parameter will be added
to `LibvirtConfigNodeDevicePciCap` to extend the PCI NIC information.

The present feature plans to use the existing API, amending the reported
profile string to the NIC capabilities string list. Users will request
capabilities and a specific profile using the same string list in the
Neutron binding profile.

blueprint intel-fortville-ddp

Change-Id: I182ee5d5293204d0fd57188d7918bd6e14975d5d

commit_message:
Cleanup of OpenDaylight on ./clean.sh

Currently, clean up(clean.sh( does not stop opendaylight
therefore some directory can not be deleted because they are
being used by OpenDaylight, which result in some data still
pending and ODL running. This patch makes sure to stop opendaylight
and clean it's data.

Change-Id: I919b62a91e400586c01c6acb87d66cac1f936fa6

'}, {'created': '2017-01-26 13:54:31.000000000', 'message': 'Apply QoS policy on network:router_gateway

All router ports (internal and external) used to be excluded from QoS policies applied on network. This patch excludles only internal router ports from network QoS policies.
This allows cloud administrators to set an egress Qos policiy to a public/external network and have the QoS policy applied on all external router ports (DVR or not). To the tenant this is also egress traffic so no confusion compared to QoS policies applied to VM ports.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I2428c2466f41a022196576f4b14526752543da7a
Closes-Bug: #1659265
Related-Bug: #1486039

commit_message:
Apply QoS policy on network:router_gateway

All router ports (internal and external) used to be excluded from QoS
policies applied on network. This patch excludes only internal router
ports from network QoS policies.
This allows cloud administrators to set an egress QoS policy to a
public/external network and have the QoS policy applied on all external
router ports (DVR or not). To the tenant this is also egress traffic so
no confusion compared to QoS policies applied to VM ports.

DocImpact

Update networking-guide/config-qos, User workflow section:
- Replace "Network owned ports" with "Internal network owned ports"

Change-Id: I2428c2466f41a022196576f4b14526752543da7a
Closes-Bug: #1659265
Related-Bug: #1486039

@Dirk; i imagine the place to do it is in openstack-infra/puppet-openafs.  that's where we install for centos as i recall"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-09-07 20:12:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

We have moved to Zuul v3 now, this change needs to be done differently
now, for current status and more information, see
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-September/122834.html'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2017-10-29 14:15:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We have switched to Zuul v3 now, this change does not apply anymore.

Learn on how to update your change with Zuul v3 at
https://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/zuulv3.html .

Simplified:
* Job definitions can be in-repo; common job definitions are in
  openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs repository
* Job scheduling can be done in-repo for project specific changes,
  common jobs are configured via
  openstack-infra/project-config/zuul.d/projects.yaml

Read the above mentioned document for finer details.

Please decide whether this change is still needed and then adopt if
for Zuul v3 or abandon it.'}, {'account_id': 23163, 'date': '2017-11-09 06:58:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I think this is already fixed.'}, {'account_id': 23163, 'date': '2017-11-09 11:34:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

No I was wrong'}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2017-11-14 07:44:47.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

requires working AFS which doesn't exist for opensuse"}]

commit_message:
Install hacking first and let it pull in right linter versions

hacking pulls in the right versions of flake8 and flake8 does
depend on the right versions of mccabe, flake8, pycodestyle by itself,
so install that one first and remove the explicit listing of those
dependencies.

Change-Id: I99ad1c1c31c4ba9e0c7e3ed692e650a9b4aba13b

commit_message:
Use service_type and service_name of nova_catalog_admin_info

Masakari has never used service_type and service_name of
nova_catalog_admin_info. However, these can be specified
when masakari creates a novalient object.
This patch modified so that masakari uses these.

Change-Id: I7fdd3b47230bea004a9129234c88d20d611814bf
Closes-Bug: #1724764

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-02 21:20:29.000000000', 'message': "Remove unused IronicObjectIndirectionAPI from ironic-api

Many moons ago, we thought that we would implement rolling upgrades
using a similar model to nova. This included adding an instance
of an IronicObjectIndirectionAPI to the ironic-api service. What
it was meant to do was for ironic-api to invoke it if it received
an IronicObject that it didn't know what to do with (because it
didn't recognize that object's version). That API would have
invoked the conductor service, asking it to generate a version
of that object which ironic-api would understood.

To use this mechanism, the assumption is that the conductor is
the gateway to the DB.

This mechanism doesn't work for ironic for a few reasons:
- ironic API reads (and occasionally) writes directly to the database.
  We don't want to change it to get access to the DB via the
  conductor all the time, since for e.g. we don't want to slow down
  the conductor
- Nova's rolling upgrade process is to initially take down all their
  conductor services (which handles their DB interactions) at the
  same time,  while their other services are still running. Unless
  ironic changes to have a similar model, we cannot take down all
  the conductor services at the same time if ironic is to provide
  services during a rolling upgrade.

Thus, this patch removes the unused IronicObjectIndirectionAPI from
the ironic-api service. Note that the IronicObjectIndrectionAPI
class itself (in ironic/objects/indirection.py) was left, in case
things ever change in the future. (And because removing that would
involve touching most, if not all, of the files in the objects/
subdirectory.)

Change-Id: I1aa264a8619105939968c0b8128b358badf00210
Closes-Bug: #1586320
"}]
commit_message:
Remove unused IronicObjectIndirectionAPI from ironic-api

Many moons ago, we thought that we would implement rolling upgrades
using a similar model to nova. This included adding an instance
of an IronicObjectIndirectionAPI to the ironic-api service. What
it was meant to do was for ironic-api to invoke it if it received
an IronicObject that it didn't know what to do with (because it
didn't recognize that object's version). That API would have
invoked the conductor service, asking it to generate a version
of that object which ironic-api would understood.

To use this mechanism, the assumption is that the conductor is
the gateway to the DB.

This mechanism doesn't work for ironic for a few reasons:
- ironic API reads (and occasionally) writes directly to the database.
  We don't want to change it to get access to the DB via the
  conductor all the time, since for e.g. we don't want to slow down
  the conductor
- Nova's rolling upgrade process is to initially take down all their
  conductor services (which handles their DB interactions) at the
  same time,  while their other services are still running. Unless
  ironic changes to have a similar model, we cannot take down all
  the conductor services at the same time if ironic is to provide
  services during a rolling upgrade.

Thus, this patch removes the unused IronicObjectIndirectionAPI from
the ironic-api service. Note that the IronicObjectIndrectionAPI
class itself (in ironic/objects/indirection.py) was left, in case
things ever change in the future. (And because removing that would
involve touching most, if not all, of the files in the objects/
subdirectory.)

Change-Id: I1aa264a8619105939968c0b8128b358badf00210
Closes-Bug: #1586320

commit_message:
Correct log message when removing a security group

When a security group is removed from a port nova
incorrectly logs this as a security group addition

Change-Id: If525313c63c4553abe8bea6f2bfaf75431ed18ea
Closes-bug: 1731889

subject: Add proposals to index
messages:
[{'account_id': 21414, 'date': '2017-11-06 07:04:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 19159, 'date': '2017-11-07 13:33:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm not sure about that. I think that most projects are using the version/approved or version/implemented structure. Some of them have in the index both approved and implemented blueprints. Also, I think that at least in some project the guideline is that if a blueprint was not implemented, it should be re-approved in the next release. 

I'm not against this change, just not 100% convinced that it's the best solution."}, {'account_id': 21414, 'date': '2017-11-09 05:49:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> I'm not against this change, just not 100% convinced that it's the
 > best solution.

I think the main purpose is to have a preview for the not implemented proposal during CI build. Some proposals contains picture, so it would nice to have preview."}, {'account_id': 21414, 'date': '2017-11-13 08:57:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 21414, 'date': '2017-11-13 09:07:13.000000000', 'content': 'Topic changed from entity-graph to docs'}, {'account_id': 19159, 'date': '2017-11-13 12:15:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> I think the main purpose is to have a preview for the not
 > implemented proposal during CI build. Some proposals contains
 > picture, so it would nice to have preview.

I agree that we should be able to see the proposals in their html format. But I think that they should remain under the scope of a version. In previous versions we've had specs that were approved but never implemented. Some of them might become outdated after a while, so I'm not sure if adding them to a one big list is the best solution. 

How about we keep the approved/implemented structure, and add approved/implemented sections to the index?"}, {'account_id': 21414, 'date': '2017-11-14 06:39:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> How about we keep the approved/implemented structure, and add
 > approved/implemented sections to the index?

Proposed in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/519547/ . Does it look better?'}, {'account_id': 21414, 'date': '2017-11-14 06:44:28.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Suppressed by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/519547/'}]

commit_message:
Add proposals to index

- move all approved proposals to `/proposals`
- use the same folder structure as previous releases for `pike`

So that we can preview the proposal on CI build

Change-Id: I63472cdfaac89cc81db77ee1df6d4be2cd8d216a
Signed-off-by: Yujun Zhang <zhang.yujunz@zte.com.cn>

I don't mind but since this is a rather simple script a log is overkill indeed.
In my mind we should strive for the simplest solution that satisfies the requirements, so in that case I'd argue we don't need logging at all and can simply print to sys.err or something.

commit_message:
Initializing logging for set ovs hostconfig command

networking_odl/cmd/set_ovs_hostconfigs.py script does not generate
logs in file or on console. These logs can be helpful for debugging
purpose. This patch enable creation of log file for this script.

Change-Id: Icc1fda55522c1ab47f5d9f07104d189fe8e7ba0a
Closes-bug: #1717520

commit_message:
devstack: add error check to _wget and _xpath

Sometimes sporadic error happens due to external network issue when
getting ODL distribution. Add more error checks to each diagnose
and exit early.

Change-Id: I697edf1e29a62dba69c5762a2a851817d2a48b87

commit_message:
Mock filecache.CACHE in unit tests

This mocks the global filecache.CACHE in unit tests that modify the
value. This is to avoid errors when other unit tests are running
at the same time, that use that same variable.

For example, ..unit.test_client.ClientTest.test_loader_arguments_token
has failed with  ...
    File "ironicclient/common/filecache.py", line 103, in retrieve_data
     data = _get_cache().get(key, expiration_time=expiry)
  AttributeError: 'int' object has no attribute 'get'

Change-Id: I84b9c6699c98d1fa642247808b6ddea4fae1e8d0

commit_message:
Add missing library 'oslo.context 'in requirement.txt

Masakari uses oslo.context library for creating RequestContext
but it is not listed as a requirement in requirement.txt.

This patch adds oslo.context in requirement.txt.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: Ibbd2fabf30ac8fca289e205180ce12ba8b1999b3

commit_message:
Fix devstack installation of masakari

Recently a commit: 188173a8072b143a28779b875af617ac7f35a92d got
merged into masakari which replaces a rpc method 'get_transport'
with 'get_rpc_transport'. The 'get_rpc_transport' expects the
oslo.messaging config option 'transport_url' [1] to be present in
the [DEFAULT] section of masakari.conf. The current masakari devstack
script doesn't add 'transport_url' in masakari.conf which results
into failure of devstack installation of masakari.

This patch fixes this issue by using an inbuilt devstack function
'iniset_rpc_backend' to add the 'transport_url' config option in
masakari.conf.

[1] * https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/master/oslo_messaging/transport.py#L44
    * https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/master/oslo_messaging/transport.py#L201

Closes-Bug: #1728544
Change-Id: I75da054c6669aa90dd96c3ede3ae98de74275de2

commit_message:
Modify unit testcases according to oslo.context

oslo.context>=2.19.1 outputs 'project' key in context's to_dict
function.
The value of 'project' key is same as 'project_id' key.

So this patch modifies unit testcases according to the above changs.

And, this patch adds oslo.context to requirements.txt.
oslo.context had been installed related to oslo.versioned object
until now.
But, it is better to describe it explicitly because Masakari uses
the library.

Change-Id: Ibebed8a4e5bfd49f192b1cf876b7538f9c057f97

commit_message:
Move and update test_resize_volume_backed_server_confirm

There is a bug in nova where the libvirt driver incorrectly removes
the local guest files for the hypervisor from shared storage because
it does not realize the instance is volume-backed. Nova runs an NFS
CI job in the experimental queue but it's not failing on resize
tests because they aren't volume-backed, so to recreate the failure
and make sure we don't regress the fix, this test is added. Nova
also runs a Ceph job which applies here too.

This moves the existing scenario test to be a compute API test. The
test ID is maintained in case people are blacklisting it, but the
slow tag is dropped because it's not a particularly slow test and
if the slow tag is applied, it won't actually be run in the jobs
that we care about testing this, e.g. NFS and Ceph jobs.

The additional wrinkle of getting the console log after the resize
is what shows the failure when the bug is not fixed, so that's added
here.

Depends-On: I29fac80d08baf64bf69e54cf673e55123174de2a

Change-Id: Id7de5186b2ea0ff7af86d9950c69203914498d88
Related-Bug: #1728603

commit_message:
Revert "Migrate oneview driver to use python-hpOneView"

Reverting these changes because python-hpOneView does not provide HTTPS
secure connection with custom CAcert and could cause a possible security issue.

This reverts commit 0ed998dfc81109f3a09100cb3b128e692be92e20.

Change-Id: I8b7f767c2bda8f3d57881ef61466e5d73c898970

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-01-02 04:11:15.000000000', 'message': 'Ignores ssl configuration option added in local.conf

If you add SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES option in local.conf, then it
is completely overridden by fixed set of services
"key,nova,cinder,glance,s-proxy,neutron" as defined in stack.sh.
The reason being stack.sh first reads SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES config
option from local.conf and then overrides it by shell variable
SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES="key,nova,cinder,glance,s-proxy,neutron".

Moved declaration of SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES before sourcing local.conf
file so that, if user wants to configure SSL for other services
then he/she can add it in local.conf like;

SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES+=<service_name>

Change-Id: I8676d50b60994d30ba998cd758c6921df49f4dbc
Closes-Bug: #1653203
'}, {'created': '2017-01-09 07:40:00.000000000', 'message': 'Ignores ssl configuration option added in local.conf

If you add SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES option in local.conf, then it
is completely overridden by fixed set of services
"key,nova,cinder,glance,s-proxy,neutron" as defined in stack.sh.
The reason being stack.sh first reads SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES config
option from local.conf and then overrides it by shell variable
SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES="key,nova,cinder,glance,s-proxy,neutron".

Appended SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES from local.conf file to already defined
sets of services so that, if user wants to configure SSL for other
services then he/she can add it in local.conf like;

SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES=<service_name>

commit_message:
Ignores ssl configuration option added in local.conf

If you add SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES option in local.conf, then it
is completely overridden by fixed set of services
"key,nova,cinder,glance,s-proxy,neutron" as defined in stack.sh.
The reason being stack.sh first reads SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES config
option from local.conf and then overrides it by shell variable
SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES="key,nova,cinder,glance,s-proxy,neutron".

Appended SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES from local.conf file to already defined
sets of services so that, if user wants to configure SSL for other
services then he/she can add it in local.conf like;

SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES=<service_name>

Change-Id: I8676d50b60994d30ba998cd758c6921df49f4dbc
Closes-Bug: #1653203

[{'created': '2017-02-23 21:30:35.000000000', 'message': "VolumeManager: Check available capacity before creating resources

For some resources, due to their inheritance of the 'host' attribute
from the source where they are asked to create from, the 'CREATE'
request doesn't go through Cinder scheduler, thus missing the chance to
check if the storage backend still have capacity.  Such resources are
snapshots, volume clones and potentially volume replication clones.  In
some cases, current implementation is fine because those new resource
would end up being in 'error' state if backend is out of capacity, but
in the case where thin-provisioning is desired and the backend has
max over-subscription ratio set, this might cause backend to serve more
than it should if the backend doesn't enforce simliar checks.

This change adds a capacity check in Volume Manager or its corresponding
taskflow before manager calls the backend driver to create the resource.

An alternative solution is the simply passing all create request to
scheduler even for those resource has known 'host'.  It'll be
implemented in separate change for comparison.

Change-Id: I0e0f10562f45eea1014d3bf6bd4d355dbfd967df
Closes-bug: #1537166

commit_message:
VolumeManager: Check available capacity before creating resources

For some resources, due to their inheritance of the 'host' attribute
from the source where they are asked to create from, the 'CREATE'
request doesn't go through Cinder scheduler, thus missing the chance to
check if the storage backend still have capacity.  Such resources are
snapshots, volume clones and potentially volume replication clones.  In
some cases, current implementation is fine because those new resource
would end up being in 'error' state if backend is out of capacity, but
in the case where thin-provisioning is desired and the backend has
max over-subscription ratio set, this might cause backend to serve more
than it should if the backend doesn't enforce simliar checks.

This change adds a capacity check in Volume Manager or its corresponding
taskflow before manager calls the backend driver to create the resource.

An alternative solution is the simply passing all create request to
scheduler even for those resource has known 'host'.  It'll be
implemented in separate change for comparison.

Change-Id: I0e0f10562f45eea1014d3bf6bd4d355dbfd967df
Closes-bug: #1537166

commit_message:
Preserve preexisting ports on container delete

This patch allow the existing port to be unbound from the
container on container delete whereupon the port will still
exist but not be associated with the container.

Change-Id: Id047ccf8b7189a0fd149ac88f3776f2573c319cd
Closes-Bug: #1704016

right, someone changed the service type to 'resource-cluster' ..."}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2017-07-13 13:57:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-07-13 14:00:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-07-13 14:07:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing

- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checkniceness-ubuntu-xenial http://logs.openstack.org/56/481356/3/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checkniceness-ubuntu-xenial/6d97798/ : SUCCESS in 7m 40s
- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-doc-publish-checkbuild http://logs.openstack.org/56/481356/3/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-doc-publish-checkbuild/53fee01/ : FAILURE in 7m 19s'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2017-07-14 00:30:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Doug, thanks for the review.

I'm wondering why senlin service type is changed from "clustering" to "resource-cluster"? Although the service today supports just VM clusters, Heat stack clusters and docker container clusters. Its design and implementation has made it very generic, with only keystone as its hard dependency on openstack. It talks to other openstack services through openstacksdk, which can be easily replaced by other things. To my knowledge, there have been efforts on building and managing kubernetes clusters using senlin. There have been practices on building hybrid clouds between openstack and other clouds (say, Alicloud). It is not limited to a "resource cluster", although the full potential may never get materialized given the current declining contributions across the community. I'm a little disappointed that the authority didn't contact us before changing the service type, for whatever reason.

Another confusion is about the "service_type.yaml" file here: https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/service-types-authority/tree/service-types.yaml
It has an alias for some services. For example, senlin still has the alias 'clustering'.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-07-14 14:56:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> @Doug, thanks for the review.
 > 
 > I'm wondering why senlin service type is changed from "clustering"
 > to "resource-cluster"? Although the service today supports just VM

I don't have any insight into that because it wasn't my decision. You should
talk to the folks that manage that registry repository. If I had to guess, I would say that "clustering" is insufficiently descriptive.

 > Another confusion is about the "service_type.yaml" file here:
 > https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/service-types-authority/tree/service-types.yaml
 > It has an alias for some services. For example, senlin still has
 > the alias 'clustering'.

Yes, that's an alias because it was being used in the past, but the preferred name
is listed separately.'}, {'account_id': 19779, 'date': '2017-11-14 02:17:05.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Senlin has been added to landing page, so abandon this one.'}]

It would be nice if this script could be split into two parts soon though, one for deploying k8s and one for deploying kola-kubernetes. This would make it easier to do one without the other.

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-07-27 18:23:24.000000000', 'message': "Python tool to bring up Kubernetes and OpenStack

This tool provides a method to deploy OpenStack on a Kubernetes Cluster using
Kolla and Kolla-Kubernetes on bare metal servers or virtual machines. Virtual
machines supported are Ubuntu and Centos.

Versions supported are 4.x (Ocata) and 5.x.

I started developing it as I worked on the project and the Deployment Guide.

In no way is this supposed to be an official production method.

It is however very simple to use (ko.py eth0 eth1), and I have verified it on
Centos and Ubuntu and Ocata and Pike.

It comes with a 'demo' mode that attempts to explain each step to the user.

It comes with lots of switches to play with different versions of all the tools
used.

Change-Id: I85858d06efcbda686bcfa177d41e6f002f98cb03

commit_message:
A python tool to orchestrate kolla kubernetes.

This tool provides a method to deploy OpenStack on a Kubernetes
Cluster using Kolla and Kolla-Kubernetes on bare metal servers
or virtual machines. Virtual machines supported are Ubuntu and
Centos.

Versions supported are 4.x (Ocata) and 5.x.

I started developing it as I worked on the project and the
Deployment Guide.

In no way is this supposed to be an official production method.

It is however very simple to use (ko.py eth0 eth1), and I have
verified it on Centos and Ubuntu and Ocata and Pike.

It comes with a 'demo' mode that attempts to explain each step
to the user.

It comes with lots of switches to play with different versions
of all the tools used.

Added a bunch of changes discovered while doing bare-metal
testing.

Added contrib/orchestration directory and using this as the
location to host user contributions.

Change-Id: I85858d06efcbda686bcfa177d41e6f002f98cb03

Don't use server_id class variable in _test_resize_server_confirm

This allows passing in a server_id which may not be the same
as the self.server_id class variable.

commit_message:
Use 'NeutronTenantNetwork' instead of 'NeutronApiNetwork' for ovn-encap-ip

ovn::controller:ovn-encap-ip is used by OVN Controllers as Geneve tunnel
end points. Presently this is configured with 'NeutronApiNetwork'. Since
the VM traffic is forwarded through the geneve end points, it makes more
sense to use 'NeutronTenantNetwork'. In the case of ML2OVS deployments,
'NeutronTenantNetwork' is used as VxLAN/GRE endpoints. Hence reusing the
same param.

Change-Id: I8b8d8c2bf20697cfb5df6a9cadadc965ae03bbb4
Closes-bug: #1731892

commit_message:
fix the exception of nova_notifier log

The LOG alaways raises the exception 'Failed to services.force_down - id: AttributeError: id'
when we print the 'response' of force_down API.

Change-Id: I45083de7e3125396767fbc00528fa4bbcb10dcd0
Signed-off-by: dongwenjuan <dong.wenjuan@zte.com.cn>

commit_message:
Fix keystone.py 'get_service_url' method parameter

Calls to 'get_service_url' should use the
'region_name' parameter. Before they were
incorrectly using 'region' as the parameter name.

Change-Id: Ic839ba6dbd5ca4dc9c7d87cf23582b8cfc393731
Closes-Bug: #1687866
(cherry picked from commit 21d89c0f641e9a03c47a7ffe42af2150af31016c)

commit_message:
Default security group update

1. What is the problem?
Currently when users update the default security group it
will raise an exception. So we can't update default security
group. When we create or delete rules it uses a synchronous way to
create or delete the related rules in bottom pod. In order
to accelerate response we need to use an asynchronous way.

2. What is the solution to the problem?
Enable default security group to support add rules and
delete rules. Using Xjob to create or delete related rules
in bottom pod.

3. What the features need to be implemented to the Tricircle
to realize the solution?
Allow users to update default security group.

Change-Id: Ibf896f15390b656bda6d438bd3176e4b15dd359c

commit_message:
Ensure that network.device type exists before using it

When passing an empty external network definition for the
undercloud, it was failing because it was assuming to have values
and a device type. Check if that exists before using it

Change-Id: I6b573485d373219d257b8c34a252d8490a4c09a0
Fixes-Bug: #1720796

commit_message:
Remove experimental jobs and sort job definitions in project.yaml

Remove the experimental jobs as they are not used in stable/ocata

Sort the job definitions in in project.yaml to make it easier to
compare and view.

Move non-voting jobs to end of list.

Delete unused playbooks due to deleting experimental jobs and some
that were unused previously.

Change-Id: I15655553e8a40857c2829089813a4935520bd06b

commit_message:
Drop extraconfig for nova-nuage

Made the Compute as a composable service with Nuage.
Moved all the Nuage specific parameters from extraconfig to be part of this service.

Change-Id: Ic83e9c18d09fbba62bb5d8a12e28a23127f4197d
(cherry picked from commit 4b1276b8f6fec22ac3764d58c4ef647535c85cb9)

commit_message:
Enable horizon plugins by default in docker

Horizon's docker image needs explicit configuration for Kolla to
enable its plugins.

This patch only enables the plugins that actually are installed.

Change-Id: I99a20abc3ac4452a3b10167e615957911327cfaa
Closes-bug: #1723929

commit_message:
Fix fixed_ips tests to skip if ip not found

Current fixed ips tests fetch the ip from server['addresses']
and call API with that ip. but it does not check if there is no
ip. That can occur when no addresses information in 'addresses'
field.

Let's skip those test if no ip is found on server side.

Change-Id: Ide965998b2d49886823e62643057c05698613169

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-11 01:27:09.000000000', 'message': "Enable other platforms to utilize diskimage-builder

This is accomplished by parameterizing two arguments
to disk-image-create which are currently hardcoded:

1) the -a arch argument
2) the absence of --no-tmpfs argument

The current package architecture as reported by Ubuntu is
passed into disk-image-create via the -a argument. This
field controls which packages are installed by DIB.

Note diskimage-builder invokes commands in a chroot'd
environment, so cross architecture builds are not supported
by definition. The platform architecture of the target
image is always the same as the caller's.

The second change is to allow the caller to specify whether
tmpfs should be disabled. This is accomplished through the use
of a new environment variable USE_TMPFS.  The default action
remains to use tmpfs.

If the user wishes to disable the use of tmpfs, the
environment variable should be set as shown below before
invoking Trove to build an image.

export USE_TMPFS=No

Note tmpfs uses half of the available free memory for a
RAM based file system. This can lead to errors in the image
building process when large compilations are performed.
In these cases, the user can try again with tmpfs disabled
simply by setting an environment variable. The alternative
is to provision another server or VM that has more memory
which is not always possible or desired.

Change-Id: Ie91209681b2291cc7a21895ad21dd1af5e82f32a

commit_message:
Enable other Ubuntu architectures to utilize diskimage-builder

This is accomplished by parameterizing the -a arch argument
which is currently hardcoded to amd64.

For Ubuntu distributions, the package architecture as reported by
Ubuntu will be passed into disk-image-create via the -a argument.
This field controls which packages are installed by DIB.

Note diskimage-builder invokes commands in a chroot'd
environment, so cross architecture builds are not supported
by definition. The platform architecture of the target
image is always the same as the caller's.

Change-Id: Ie91209681b2291cc7a21895ad21dd1af5e82f32a

commit_message:
Remove the existing snapshots from the backend

We only have to remove the existing snapshots
for resources when stack delete.

Change-Id: Ia195f3c3380fe71e0888c8291209dd4562318951
Closes-Bug: #1716612
(cherry picked from commit 1861ad88670581e0658c8010950edd54ea4de422)

commit_message:
Set `public` as update allowed for cluster template

Considering with cluster dependency with cluster template.
`public` is the only update-able property when cluster depends on
that cluster tempate. Therefore, we allow update on that property.

Change-Id: I04a45b6a6b70de2cc4886f5d4ada170f959c309a

commit_message:
Fix featureset024 to deploy Ceph not in containers via puppet-ceph

With change [1] we changed the default behavior of the
storage-environment.yaml file to deploy Ceph in containers using
ceph-ansible; featureset024 instead is not using containers, so
we should update it to make it use puppet-ceph instead.

1. I1dea3b7665dc0da2ab30a89e077ba36cd36b05fd

Change-Id: I444760bf168af466411746023523c1b681d0ccda
Closes-Bug: #1731282

commit_message:
Set keystone notification topics if ceilometer is enabled

This sets the keystone notification topics only if ceilometer is
enabled. This mitigates the issue of keystone sending notifications
when nobody is receiving them.

Closes-Bug: #1729293
Depends-On: I4dcce73446633c08ea37ba567610eec398094036
Change-Id: I063af5e642388acc180cb8e728481c5a36cc8ddc
(cherry picked from commit 4adb82d03ddd72191bb379f277374a0a5720bbc4)

commit_message:
use addr pairs api def from lib

The allowed address pairs extension's API definition was rehomed into
neutron-lib with I7958a2d6f470f088ca2cb8ad638c075788f22851. This patch
consumes the API definition in neutron.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: I46cfeee9711973ec15881c8dc2bd0bf763bc2226

commit_message:
Make keystone notification topics configurable

By default keystone sends notifications to the 'notifications'
topic. This is consumed by default by ceilometer. However, when
ceilometer is not enabled, rabbitmq accumulates these notifications
since nothing is consuming them. This results in the queue consuming
rabbitmq's memory.

With this capability, we can now dynamically configure notification
topics depending on the 'keystone_notification_topics' hiera key.

Related-Bug: #1729293
Change-Id: I4dcce73446633c08ea37ba567610eec398094036
(cherry picked from commit bbe7d9effe51324ef5fa75e40f9d0ca74544d484)

commit_message:
Lazy load all configuration options

This is a follow up to Change #444040.

Configuration options should always be lazy loaded,
this is to prevent changes in import order from
interfering with the configuration variable being
instantiated properly.

Change-Id: I3040108128ba56746ed4d5d688b8b8d33da753fc
Closes-Bug: #1694538

commit_message:
Keystone: Enable notification topics to be configured

This enables the configuration of notification topics via the
KeystoneNotificationTopics parameter.

Change-Id: I224e730e41e1bcb703e5deebfab3ca74f08faa02
Related-Bug: #1729293
(cherry picked from commit 3de75ccea06a160f8afb21f9da461109a08f7cbc)

commit_message:
use dvr api def from neutron-lib

The dvr extension's API definition was rehomed into neutron-lib with
commit I6d98e83287833882515240d7db1faa4a1deb7da1
This patch consumes it by removing the rehomed code and using the
APIExtensionDescriptor for the extensions parent class.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: Id5f0be33b036370b7545258a321830fdaa4dc0da

commit_message:
Remove rbac-policy callback into lib

Since most callback resources are located in neutron-lib,
rbac-policy still in [1], we can move it to the lib.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/db/rbac_db_mixin.py#L31

Change-Id: Ib59703496bc8d13619358c39f5e01c00ee7211f4

commit_message:
docs: Add primary_key attribute key

While reading the contributor guide, it seems lack of description
of primary_key. [1]

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron-lib/blob/master/neutron_lib/api/definitions/base.py

Fix RBAC POST parameter of api-ref

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Adds IPinIP protocol

Neutron doesn't support the IP-in-IP protocol by name in
security group rules. With this change a user can now
declare the IP-in-IP protocol by using the name 'ipip'

Note: This doesn't fix an underlying problem
with the Neutron protocol number validator, but
serves as a work around for users wanting to use
the IP-in-IP protocol.

Partial-bug: #1716045

Change-Id: I18e5e42b687e12b64f5a9c523a912c8dd1afa9d2

commit_message:
fix up dvr api def exceptions

Commit I6d98e83287833882515240d7db1faa4a1deb7da1 rehomed the DVR
API def into neutron-lib, but:
- The DVRMacAddressNotFound exception was never rehomed. While not used
externally today [1], it's foreseeable that implementations of the
extension will need it.
- The exception message used in HostMacAddressGenerationFailure of the
rehome patch mentions "DVR". This should not be the case as the
HostMacAddressGenerationFailure is generic in nature.

[1] http://codesearch.openstack.org/?q=DVRMacAddressNotFound

Change-Id: I88e1aa2acf22389f69cb7d5704c80a5eb72a9bbe

subject: Add metadata checksums to old objects in auditor.
messages:
[{'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2017-10-20 00:15:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2017-10-20 16:29:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Pretty sure we need to update mem_diskfile for the signature change. Probably want to handle IOErrors that may get thrown when writing, too. I think we just ignore them? Not sure there's much more we *can* do -- log a warning, I guess?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2017-10-20 18:27:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2017-10-20 18:36:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2017-10-20 21:42:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

> In this case, the error handling in failsafe_object_audit catches it.

You mean _failsafe_read_metadata, yeah? So if we have an object that's otherwise perfectly valid, just doesn't have the metadata checksum, and we *can't* add that checksum... we quarantine it?

*shrug* Seems like a bit of an overreaction, but I guess..."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2017-10-20 22:15:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Oh right, there's two layers of failsafe in there.

For this to end up harmful, you've got to have an auditor which (a) can read xattrs on an inode, (b) cannot set an xattr on that same inode, and (c) can quarantine the object.

If you've just got the typical permission problems, like you plug dead box A's drives into live box B, but the "swift" user has different UIDs on A and B, then your auditors will complain and moan a lot, but won't be able to do anything to the data.

Are you considering plumbing through a new exception for this case and logging an error? I'm certainly open to suggestions here.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2017-11-10 00:49:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2017-11-10 01:06:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2017-11-10 01:13:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

Bah! I'm torn about whether to change my vote over it though..."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2017-11-13 18:23:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2017-11-13 18:26:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2017-11-13 20:23:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2

lgtm, ran automated tests on my machine and also tested manually by deleting the extra xattr and running the auditor once to see it be put back.'}]

commit_message:
Add metadata checksums to old objects in auditor.

When the object auditor examines an object, it will now add any
missing metadata checksums. This goes for both .data and .meta files,
but not .ts files, as tombstones don't live very long anyway.

Change-Id: I9417a8b0cc5099470845c0504c834746188d89e8

commit_message:
use router az api def from neutron-lib

The route availability zone extension's API definition was rehomed into
neutron-lib with commit I8bc54b581c26d8472e38efaaa63741785e07d2b8
This patch consumes the API definition by:

- Removing the rehomed code from neutron.
- Using the APIExtensionDescriptor for the extension classes parent
thereby leveraging the values from the API defintion.
- Updating any references to now use the neutron-lib code.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: I70db0cebe7656fde6ff1fe724fe604eb70e26f75

commit_message:
Replace TestCase with NoDBTestCase

It was suggested that we replace TestCase with NoDBTestCase [1]. This
does two things. First it prevents the test case setup from running the
database schema migrations unnecessarily which should improve
performance. Second it will cause the test to fail if the code does
touch the DB when the developer is claiming that it shouldn't.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/409404/46/nova/tests/unit/virt/powervm/test_media.py

Change-Id: I8bcc9cbdcadd9fe89a4450ca405387899baa9fc3

Use uuid instead of deprecated node-uuid

  falling back to insecure Math.random() warning in tests

commit_message:
Add constraints to service Debug flags

The service debug flags (e.g. BarbicanDebug), allow the deployer to set
the verbose logging for a specific service. They are strings to allow
folks to set it up regardless of the global Debug flag being set.

This commit adds a constraint to set the allowed values for these
parameters. It is based on a subset of the underlying implementation
that sets this flag (which uses any2bool).

Change-Id: I35e7a7ee35aefb7108ec6b0bb8f3124610fb97ee

commit_message:
Ignore missing rendered heat envs in prepare

Since we use j2 templates for some of the heat environments, and at the
moment they are rendered when uploading them to swift at the beginning
of the deployment workflow, it is possible that one of the heat
environment file passed to the prepare command is, or references a file
that is, not yet rendered.

This commit implements a custom object_request() function that makes
process_multiple_environments_and_files() ignore the missing files.

Change-Id: I6f31898ca3db9563d3d8e8e6e0a9f0cdaebf24ca
Co-Authored-By: Thomas Hervé <therve@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1730650
(cherry picked from commit a68cbfd5157ec367020a753905f7e1802d127a0f)

commit_message:
Fix fetching ironic nodes for updating resource classes on upgrade

The correct value of "limit" to fetch all nodes is 0, not -1.
This issue prevents all nodes to be updated on upgrade, breaking scaling.

Change-Id: I1beac8fb463a6ecfaac3dc7f176d82beba7ffdc7
Closes-Bug: #1731885

commit_message:
Do not failed update if no container registry is set

When the init minor update step is run without any
container registry file, the cli should not raise
an exception. We should accept to run it, even if
the container won't be update. It could be usefull
for only run package update on the env.

Change-Id: I73d86d1ec61b9bb6d5f4a5ea8a9bc545ac963420
Closes-Bug: #1730687
(cherry picked from commit a7166208b7cdd988590bd1e3b1c1f1453d29d1e1)

commit_message:
Add validation task in docker services [Swift]

Docker services are missing the pre-upgrade validation task
in the upgrade_tasks section which verifies if the service
is running before going on with the upgrade.

Change-Id: I16f38d9e1042c5d83455a28882b4a024aac27699
Partial-Bug: #1704389

commit_message:
Add validation task in docker services [Mistral]

Docker services are missing the pre-upgrade validation task
in the upgrade_tasks section which verifies if the service
is running before going on with the upgrade.

Change-Id: Ic1cc3fb7cf59eaa67dd74e762f534f97b988541e
Partial-Bug: #1704389

commit_message:
Add validation task in docker services [Gnocchi]

Docker services are missing the pre-upgrade validation task
in the upgrade_tasks section which verifies if the service
is running before going on with the upgrade.

Change-Id: I3db9c13709ef0dcc71fbaf51b80c498d7998daac
Partial-Bug: #1704389

commit_message:
Fix logic error

if security_sshd_permit_root_login is not set to yes, we should
override this and template a "no", instead of templating a "no"
when the value is set to yes.

Change-Id: I747a8818762119eee63fa03d175b66ae4021f6da
Closes-Bug: #1685194

commit_message:
Add support for multiple/no L3 addresses on port

As a port may have multiple IP addresses (IPv4/IPv6), we should check
all of them and not just look at the first one as the current code does.
Also the new code handles the valid scenario where the port has no L3
address at all.

Change-Id: I616731d31e1ec12d50c919d393d0d3990e8d2547
Partial-Bug: #1728518

commit_message:
Split build-wheel-mirror into 2 jobs

It is hard to trace 4 nodes going at once, so group these into
ubuntu-trusty and ubuntu-xenial for now.  Once everything is working
as expected, we could consider rolling this back. But honestly, 4
nodes is a little much.

Change-Id: I2cdc2ded48ee50491df7ee9c3b84c6f60c870318
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Don't include properties data in replacement resource

In convergence when we want to create a replacement resource, don't pass
it the properties data of the old resource. It's a brand new resource
and doesn't have any properties yet. It's undesirable to have old
property values related to some different resource stored for it.

Change-Id: Id975c456fa9ec4797b634760010990e5097d24ca

FWIW, I think Monty was the big proponent for keeping things around. I pinged him on openstack-dev, and while he's still not a fan of this, there are other projects that are removing deprecated APIs now and it should be OK for Cinder to do the same.

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-dev/%23openstack-dev.2017-08-31.log.html#t2017-08-31T14:53:10"}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2017-09-04 15:53:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

One question I had in relation to this - should I also remove the api-ref for v1 along with this? Or leave it for historical reference?

I'm somewhat on the fence, but I think leaving it in may potentially lead to confusion."}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2017-09-04 15:56:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ok, if other groups are doing it and Monty is ok with that, then I think we should lean towards removal.  As for the API-Ref.  I wonder if we can move it to a 'retired' section and make note that the code has been removed?"}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2017-09-04 16:01:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

That works. In the API ref we do have it labelled as "(DEPRECATED)" right now. We could change the wording from deprecated to some like "LEGACY" or even "For reference only".'}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2017-09-04 19:48:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 9535, 'date': '2017-09-05 09:37:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I agree we should remove v1, but the patch is incomplete:

- You have to update api-paste.ini
- You have to remove enable_v1_api from cinder/common/config.py
- Remove v1 code from cinder/api/__init__.py:root_app_factory

As for the documentation we have to keep it, but I agree we should make some remark on it, probably setting it as LEGACY like you mentioned but specifying on which Cinder releases it was available.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2017-09-05 15:43:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 15831, 'date': '2017-09-05 16:39:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Remove API v1

The v1 API has been deprecated for many releases now. We have not
been able to remove it due to SDKs and tooling being slow to
update. This is the latest attempt to see if it has been long
enough.

Change-Id: I03bf2db5bd7e2fdfb4f6032758ccaf2b348a82ba

commit_message:
Move check_ha_state_for_router() into notification code

As soon as we call router_info.initialize(), we could
possibly try and process a router.  If it is HA, and
we have not fully initialized the HA port or keepalived
manager, we could trigger an exception.

Move the call to check_ha_state_for_router() into the
update notification code so it's done after the router
has been created.  Updated the functional tests for this
since the unit tests are now invalid.

Also added a retry counter to the RouterUpdate object so
the l3-agent code will stop re-enqueuing the same update
in an infinite loop.  We will delete the router if the
limit is reached.

Finally, have the L3 HA code verify that ha_port and
keepalived_manager objects are valid during deletion since
there is no need to do additional work if they are not.

Conflicts:
      neutron/agent/l3/agent.py

Change-Id: Iae65305cbc04b7af482032ddf06b6f2162a9c862
Closes-bug: #1726370
(cherry picked from commit d2b909f5339e72f84de797977384e4164d72a154)

commit_message:
Enable reset keypair while rebuilding instance

This patch adds `key_name` param to instance rebuild
API. Then the user could reset the instance keypair
when rebuilding. If set key_name to None, the API
will unset the keypair of the instance.

APIImpact

Implements blueprint: rebuild-keypair-reset

Change-Id: I23886a89c25f811cfbe7e2500ce7ff52f9162966

commit_message:
Revert "Fix persistent information when getting boot device"

Reverting these changes because python-hpOneView does not provide HTTPS
secure connection with custom CAcert and could cause a possible security issue.

This reverts commit 5de0ccccd69258b930ed8ab7b91ca3a1aad705c1.

Change-Id: I4cf20e59fac71ef2d548182c084bcbed2193fada

commit_message:
Puppet OpenStack queens-1 round 2

The previous attempt at releasing puppet-ceilometer, puppet-glance,
puppet-gnocchi, puppet-magnum, and puppet-swift failed because the
release hashes did not properly include the bindep.txt changes required
to allow the release jobs to build the puppet modules.

Change-Id: I74de6d68075e0cf02adcab260863c1a4e63993a4

> Man if i could -2 this i would. This is a massive security
 > vulnerability.
 > 
 > Why not just bind mount in libmodules? Then you are assured to load
 > the right modules, even if it is within the container
 > 
 > /lib/modules/:/lib/modules/:ro

That wont work across distros'}, {'account_id': 8898, 'date': '2017-10-10 19:18:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

which distro's won't work bind-mounting lib modules?"}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2017-10-10 19:23:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

fedora host with ubuntu or centos containers will break. fedora for the past year or so has been wrapping thier modules with xz 
compression rather than the traditional gz compression. The older versions of modprobe in ubuntu and centos don't know how to deal with this.

So any host with xz modules won't work with stable distros like ubuntu lts and centos until they catch up.


Still not a good reason to binding the whole root filesystem. I would argue the majority of people are going to be using ubuntu on ubuntu or centos on centos. If this breaks a *common* use case, then its worth discussing.

And remember, in the event of one of these "uncommon" usecases, you can always just document saying "you need to modprobe these yourself, or put them in modprobe.conf" and then ignore modprobe failures.'}, {'account_id': 23928, 'date': '2017-10-10 19:46:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

> fedora host with ubuntu or centos containers will break. fedora for
 > the past year or so has been wrapping thier modules with xz
 > compression rather than the traditional gz compression. The older
 > versions of modprobe in ubuntu and centos don't know how to deal
 > with this.
 > 
 > So any host with xz modules won't work with stable distros like
 > ubuntu lts and centos until they catch up.
 > 
 > 
 > Still not a good reason to binding the whole root filesystem. I
 > would argue the majority of people are going to be using ubuntu on
 > ubuntu or centos on centos. If this breaks a *common* use case,
 > then its worth discussing.
 > 
 > And remember, in the event of one of these "uncommon" usecases, you
 > can always just document saying "you need to modprobe these
 > yourself, or put them in modprobe.conf" and then ignore modprobe
 > failures.

Sams point is correct here - I'll update the ps to load the modules a different way.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-10-10 19:47:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Kernel Modules: Load via chroot into host

This PS moves the loading of kernel modules required by services to
being perfromed via a chroot on the host, this ensures that the correct
module is found and provides compatibility across distros.

Change-Id: I889fdd047a24bf4b123dadf9f6d6e6e8079d69d1

commit_message:
Add support to set host param

Lets expose this param so we can override the host param in
ceilometer config. Without this, some metrics from nova wont
make it as in some cases the fqdn might not match hostname.

Partial-bug: #1721054

Change-Id: I421a61dc31bd10fec0a10bf7e867001cf4dd3f02
(cherry picked from commit 4a249ae38c62d2670a37990c7cb44abd77ae3aa4)

Looking at git logs there isn't really enough information to know what

that the issues there could have been fixed with all of the fixing zuul
has gotten post v3 rollout.

Let's turn it back on again so that we can either determine it is fine

Change-Id: If89db9dee8522256310ee354a7055f36adf5d832

commit_message:
Enable citycloud sto2 in nodepool

Looking at git logs there isn't really enough information to know what
needs to be debugged in sto2, also sto2 was disabled long enough ago
that the issues there could have been fixed with all of the fixing zuul
has gotten post v3 rollout.

Let's turn it back on again so that we can either determine it is fine
now or generate the necessary info to debug it. Also at the summit I met
some citycloud folks who should be able to help us debug it from their
end so now is a good time to do debugging.

Change-Id: If89db9dee8522256310ee354a7055f36adf5d832

commit_message:
RabbitMQ should use net_ticktime

We no longer need to force low-level TCP timeouts for dead client
detection, but should continue tuning the timeout for dead peer
detection between cluster nodes.  Using the erlang net_ticktime option
is preferrable here.

Closes-Bug: 1717006
Change-Id: Ibd29c03bd69818d79396c379a2d638c018a04b82

commit_message:
zuul: Centralize irrelevant-files in legacy-ironic-lib-dsvm-base

Create a new base job: legacy-ironic-lib-dsvm-base

Define 'irrelevant-files' in legacy-ironic-lib-dsvm-base and remove
them from project.yaml. This means we only define 'irrelevant-files'
once. Also makes project.yaml much easier to read.

Fix the 'irrelevant-files' section to make sure we do test when
changes are made to 'requirements.txt'.

Sort the jobs lists in project.yaml.

Change-Id: I0534be1ff4ac4d3d2e40f282966683c7b60fc7ba

commit_message:
Gate: Add linter gate and path options to OSH-Infra

This patch set adds a zuul v3 trailing whitespace linter gate to
the OSH-infra repository.

It additionally updates the work_dir path to account for being
launched as a dependant project in zuulv3.

Change-Id: I680a5942f008a6246641bebca7d9880a7824f2ce

commit_message:
Refactored Neutron tempest plugin directory structure

* switch from neutron.tests.tempest to neutron_tempest_plugin
* Cleaned up README.rst and setup.cfg
* Use neutron_tempest_plugin as a tempest plugin package
* Fixed gitreview
* Keeping flake8 Ignores in tox.ini as tempest plugin is
  imported from neutron codebase.

Add config sample to compute-hyperv docs

This change adds an automatically generated config sample to the
compute-hyperv docs.

The config sample is generated each time the docs are built, using
the oslo.config sphinxconfiggen extension.
